QUENNE COMPREHENSIVE TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS

Version 1.0 | Quantum-Edge-NeuroNorphic Engine

---

1. ARCHITECTURAL OVERVIEW

1.1 Core Design Philosophy

QUENNE implements a cognitive continuum where quantum, neuromorphic, and edge computing resources form a unified substrate. The architecture follows five foundational principles:

1. Quantum-Neural Correspondence: Quantum states map to cognitive states
2. Energy-Aware Computation: All operations optimized for joules-per-inference
3. Emergent Homeostasis: System self-regulates via feedback loops at all layers
4. Semantic Coherence: Information carries meaning and context intrinsically
5. Temporal Plasticity: Architecture adapts to time-critical vs. deliberative tasks

1.2 System Topology

```
[Edge Nodes] <-> [6G Semantic Fabric] <-> [Neuromorphic Mesh] <-> [Quantum Coherence Pool]
      |                   |                       |                       |
  Physical World     Meaning-Aware           Associative            Superposition
  Interaction        Communication            Memory                Processing
```

---

2. LAYER-BY-LAYER SPECIFICATIONS

2.1 Quantum State Inference Layer (Q-SIL)

2.1.1 Quantum Processing Unit (QPU) Requirements

· Qubit Count: Minimum 1,000 logical qubits (error-corrected)
· Coherence Time: >10 seconds for cognitive operations
· Gate Fidelity: >99.99% for single-qubit, >99.9% for two-qubit
· Quantum Volume: Minimum 2¹⁶
· Specialized Operations:
  · Quantum amplitude estimation for probability gradients
  · Grover-like search for associative memory recall
  · Variational quantum eigensolvers for state optimization

2.1.2 State-Aware Inference Engine

```
Input: Quantum state |ψ⟩, Semantic context C
Output: Evolved state |ψ'⟩, Inference confidence P

Algorithm:
1. Initialize |ψ⟩ based on input context C
2. Apply quantum neural network layers (parameterized unitaries)
3. Measure observable O for inference result
4. Calculate probability amplitudes for confidence scoring
5. Optionally preserve |ψ'⟩ for continuous reasoning
```

2.1.3 Quantum-Classical Interface

· Latency: <100μs round-trip between QPU and classical controllers
· Bandwidth: 100 Gb/s sustained data transfer
· Error Mitigation: Real-time error correction via surface codes
· State Preparation: <1ms for arbitrary state initialization

2.2 Neuromorphic Cognition Layer (N-CL)

2.2.1 Neuromorphic Processing Core Specifications

· Neuron Count: 10⁷ synthetic neurons per chip (scalable to 10⁹ via mesh)
· Synapse Density: 10¹⁰ synapses per chip (4-bit weight precision minimum)
· Spike Rate: 10⁸ spikes/second per chip
· Power Efficiency: <10 pJ per spike event
· Plasticity Rules: Support for STDP, Hebbian, and homeostatic learning

2.2.2 Associative Memory Field Architecture

```
Memory Organization:
- Content-addressable storage with similarity thresholds
- Hierarchical organization (episodic → semantic → procedural)
- Cross-modal associations (visual ↔ auditory ↔ semantic)
- Temporal context tagging with 1ms resolution

Retrieval Protocol:
1. Partial pattern P presented to input field
2. Parallel similarity computation across all memories
3. Top-K matches retrieved with confidence scores
4. Pattern completion via attractor network dynamics
5. Temporal reconstruction if time-tagged data
```

2.2.3 Learning Mechanisms

· Continuous Learning: Online, incremental without catastrophic forgetting
· Meta-Learning: Learning rate adaptation based on prediction error
· Transfer Learning: Cross-domain knowledge transfer via shared embeddings
· Consolidation: Active memory replay during low-activity periods

2.3 Edge-Actuated Embodiment Layer (EA-EL)

2.3.1 Edge Node Specifications

```
Type A (Lightweight Sensor Node):
- Processing: 4 neuromorphic cores (100K neurons each)
- Sensors: Multi-modal (vision, audio, inertial, environmental)
- Actuators: 4-DOF minimum
- Power: Energy harvesting capable (solar/RF/kinetic)
- Connectivity: 6G mmWave and sub-6GHz

Type B (Gateway Node):
- Processing: 32 neuromorphic cores + FPGA for quantum interface
- Quantum Link: Coherent or entanglement distribution capability
- Power: Grid-connected with 8-hour battery backup
- Storage: 1TB NVMe with 1PB/day write endurance
```

2.3.2 Situational Awareness System

· Multi-Sensor Fusion: Kalman filtering with uncertainty quantification
· Object Tracking: Up to 1,000 simultaneous objects at 60Hz update rate
· Intent Prediction: Bayesian inference over possible actor goals
· Anomaly Detection: Autoencoder-based with <1% false positive rate
· 3D Mapping: Real-time SLAM at 5cm resolution in 100m radius

2.3.3 Cyber-Physical Interface

· Latency: <5ms sensor-to-actuator loop for critical responses
· Safety: Triple-modular redundancy for critical actuators
· Adaptability: Physical configuration recognition and auto-calibration
· Compliance: ISO 13849 PLd (Performance Level d) minimum

2.4 Resilience & Homeostasis Layer (R-HL)

2.4.1 Homeostatic Regulation System

```
Regulated Parameters:
- Computational load (target: 70% utilization)
- Energy consumption (target: optimal joules/task)
- Memory allocation (dynamic based on priority)
- Network latency (maintains QoS thresholds)
- Thermal management (keeps components <85°C)

Regulation Mechanisms:
- Proportional-Integral-Derivative (PID) controllers for each parameter
- Predictive adjustment based on historical patterns
- Emergency protocols for boundary violations
- Graceful degradation rather than catastrophic failure
```

2.4.2 Immune-Style Security

```
Security Components:
- Pattern Recognition: Detect anomalies in system behavior
- Distributed Ledger: Tamper-proof audit trail of all state changes
- Quantum Key Distribution: For all inter-node communications
- Moving Target Defense: Dynamic reconfiguration to prevent exploitation
- Auto-Containment: Isolate compromised components automatically

Response Time:
- Threat detection: <100ms from initial manifestation
- Containment decision: <50ms after detection
- System reconfiguration: <1s for full topology change
```

2.4.3 Energy Management

· Power Sources: Grid, battery, harvesting (priority-based switching)
· Dynamic Voltage/Frequency Scaling: Per-core optimization
· Task Migration: Move computation to most energy-efficient nodes
· Sleep Scheduling: Predictive wake-up based on anticipated needs
· Regenerative Operation: Use computation heat for other systems when possible

---

3. CROSS-LAYER FUNCTIONAL SPECIFICATIONS

3.1 Quantum-Neuromorphic Interface (QNI)

· Protocol: Quantum measurement to spike train conversion
· Latency: <10μs for state transfer
· Fidelity: >99% state preservation during conversion
· Bandwidth: Equivalent to 10⁶ neuron activations per second

3.2 6G Semantic Signaling Protocol

```
Frame Structure:
- Preamble: Network synchronization
- Header: Source, destination, intent, priority
- Payload: Data + semantic annotations
- Footer: Integrity check, next-hop instructions

Key Features:
- Intent-based routing (not just address-based)
- Quality of Experience (QoE) metrics in header
- Dynamic spectrum sharing based on content priority
- End-to-end latency: <1ms for critical signals
```

3.3 State Synchronization Mechanism

```
Synchronization Protocol:
1. Global quantum clock provides μs-accurate timing
2. Neuromorphic oscillators phase-lock to quantum clock
3. Edge nodes synchronize via 6G network timing
4. State vectors exchanged during coherence windows
5. Consensus mechanism resolves conflicting observations
```

3.4 Cognitive State Transitions

```
State Space Representation:
- Dimensions: Current goal, emotional valence, attention focus, confidence
- Transitions: Governed by quantum-inspired Hamiltonian
- Measurement: Partial collapse when interacting with environment

Transition Rules:
- Goal conflict → superposition of possible actions
- High uncertainty → exploration of state space
- High confidence → exploitation of known strategies
- Novel situations → creative state generation
```

